<h2 id="website-enumeration">Website Enumeration</h2>

<p>Navigating to http://172.31.1.6 we get redirected to http://172.31.1.6/users/sign_in</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/gitlab.png" alt="GitLab Sign-In" /></p>

<p>Trying to navigate to another page in robots.txt redirects us to the login page or a limited version of the website. LetŌĆÖs create an account an maybe we can get more access. I signed up with a random username and email and was given access to the rest of the platform.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/loggedin.png" alt="Logged in" /></p>

<p>Navigating around the website it seems pretty sparse and there isnŌĆÖt much that has been uploaded. One interesting page, however, is the <strong>/public</strong> directory.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/public.png" alt="/public" /></p>

<p>It looks like there are three git repositories owned by the user <strong>jonathan</strong>. LetŌĆÖs make a note of that username and take a look through the repos. The ruby-on-rails and first-project repos only have an initial commit on them, and not really much to look at. LetŌĆÖs dig a little deeper into the <strong>CMS</strong> directory:</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/cms.png" alt="CMS Commits" /></p>

<p>There are three commits made by jonathan, with two of them on the same file. It seems that jonathan accidentally included his password in the first commit, and took it out in the second.</p>

