<h1 id="exploitation">Exploitation</h1>

<h2 id="user-flag">User Flag</h2>

<p>So, now we have a password. The question is, where do we use it? Since it was used as a SQL password in config.php, I thought there might have been a mySQL server on the box. Unfortunately, that didnŌĆÖt lead anywhere. However, we are able to log into GitLab using those credentials:</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/jonathan_logged.png" alt="We're in!" /></p>

<p>Jonathan has a hidden repository it seems called <strong>security</strong>. If we open it up we see that he has his private SSH key stored in the repository. Jackpot!</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/ssh_key.png" alt="SSH Key" /></p>

<p>LetŌĆÖs copy that to our local machine, and try to SSH into the box using the stolen key.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/oops.png" alt="Doesn't work" /></p>
<blockquote>
  <p>Note: jonathan_ssh.key is the same as id_rsa from the repo</p>
</blockquote>

<p>We need his passphrase to be able to log into the box. Luckily, we can use <strong>john</strong> to get that passphrase. First, we use <strong>ssh2john.py</strong> to convert the key to a formate readable by john. Then, we just run john on the file (using the rockyou.txt password list) and we will eventually get the passphrase.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/ssh2john.png" alt="ssh2john" /></p>

<p>Jinkies! Looks like we have our passphrase! LetŌĆÖs try to ssh back into the machine.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/ssh.png" alt="Now we're REALLY in!" /></p>

<p>From here we can get our <strong>access.txt</strong> (which I wonŌĆÖt show in this writeup).</p>

<h2 id="root-flag">Root Flag</h2>

<p>Now that we have user access, letŌĆÖs try to find a way to escalate our privileges. LetŌĆÖs upload LinEnum.sh by setting up an http server on our local machine using <code class="highlighter-rouge">python -m SimpleHTTPServer 80</code> in the directory that has the sh file. Then we can use <strong>wget</strong> to download it onto leakage, and the run it. Looking through the ouput, one bit catches my eye:</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/suid.png" alt="LinEnum.sh" /></p>

<p><strong>Nano</strong> (a cli-based text editor) has SUID set, which means we can run it with root privileges even if we arenŌĆÖt root. What can we do with that ability? We can essentially open and view any file on the machine. LetŌĆÖs take a look at <strong>/etc/shadow</strong>.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/shadow.png" alt="/etc/shadow" /></p>

<p>Eureka! We can now pretty easily get the root userŌĆÖs password. LetŌĆÖs copy the hash (from the first ŌĆś:ŌĆÖ to the second ŌĆś:ŌĆÖ) and run it through <strong>hashcat</strong>. The beginning of the hash starts with a $6$ which means it is a SHA-512 hash. You can look up different hash types accepted by hashcat <a href="https://hashcat.net/wiki/doku.php?id=example_hashes">here</a>, with an example of each type. LetŌĆÖs try to reverse that hash:</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/hashcat.png" alt="hashcat" /></p>

<p>Now that weŌĆÖve reverse the hash, letŌĆÖs try to log in to the root user.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/writeups/leakage/root.png" alt="We've done it!" /></p>

<p>From here we can get <strong>system.txt</strong> (which, once again, I will not be showing).</p>
